occurrences.line_text: Ladies can laugh at Ladies, Knights at Knights,
Ladies can laugh at Ladies, Knights at Knights,
Fit for such Ladies and such louely knights:
With th'Elfin Knight, her Ladies best beloued;
Amongst loose Ladies, lapped in delight:
And then both Knights enuide, & Ladies eke did spight.
Such was this Ladies fit, in her loues fond accusing.
That Ladies part, and to the Souldan lout:
Vnto that Damzell in her Ladies right,
Towards my Ladies presence by you ment,
To seeke for succour of this Ladies gieft:
In th'hearing of full many Knights and Ladies gent.
The which whylome that Ladies owne had bene;
Well tride in all thy Ladies troubles than,
Faire Lords and Ladies, which about you dwell,
Where curteous Knights and Ladies most did won
Good Knights and Ladies true, and many else destroyd.
But they that Ladies lockes doe shaue away,
With beards of Knights and locks of Ladies lynd.
To take defiaunce at a Ladies word
And is the boast of that proud Ladies threat,
Next that ye Ladies ayde in euery stead and stound.
For Ladies seruice, and for loues delight,
Faith to his knight, and truth to Ladies all,
To giue faire colour to that Ladies cause in sight.
Till to that Ladies fathers house he came;
Vnlesse thou dare for thy deare Ladies sake,
Yet for the feeble Ladies sake, full loth
Behinde his Ladies backe, who to him cryde,
But chaste him still, for all his Ladies cry;
Drawne with that Ladies loud and piteous shright,
But that same Ladies hurts no herbe he found,
Till that his Ladies sight he mote attaine,
Such were this Ladies pangs and dolorous assay.
Gainst errant Knights and Ladies thou dost reare,
This was Disdaine, who led that Ladies horse
Y e gentle Ladies, in whose soueraine powre
And sure I weene, had not the Ladies cry
There he a troupe of Ladies dauncing found
Three other Ladies did both daunce and sing,
That all those Ladies, which thou sawest late,
Some stird the molten owre with ladles great;
With hookes and ladles, as need did require;
Great Lady of the greatest Isle, whose light
His Lady sad to see his sore constraint,
And with the Lady backward sought to wend;
Now (sayd the Lady) draweth toward night,
Had made a Lady of that other Spright,
He taught to imitate that Lady trew,
Then seemed him his Lady by him lay,
Lo there before his face his Lady is,
Come see, where your false Lady doth her honour staine.
A goodly Lady clad in scarlot red,
The Lady when she saw her champion fall,
And said, Faire Lady hart of flint would rew
And his new Lady it endured not.
And to this wretched Lady, my deare loue,
To loue this gentle Lady, whom ye see,
Now not a Lady, but a seeming tree;
That had a like faire Lady by his syde,
Like a faire Lady, but did fowle Duessa hyde.
His Lady left as a prise martiall,
Then turning to his Lady, dead with feare her found.
Such were the labours of this Lady meeke,
But yet his Lady did so well him cheare,
Of her, that was the Lady of that Pallace bright.
And false Duessa seeming Lady faire,
Emongst the rest rode that false Lady faire,
A wondrous way it for this Lady wrought,
And there begotten of a Lady myld,
Straunge Lady, in so straunge habiliment,
Were it not better, I that Lady had,
Whom when his Lady saw, to him she ran
Faire Lady, then said that victorious knight,
Well worthy impe, said then the Lady gent,
Then bad the knight his Lady yede aloofe,
So faire and fresh that Lady shewd her selfe in sight.
Deare Lady how shall I declare thy cace,
Where sate a gentle Lady all alone,
Fit to inflame faire Lady with loues rage,
Ay me, deare Lady, which the image art
Speake, O deare Lady speake: help neuer comes too late.
Tell then, ï¿½ Lady tell, what fatall priefe
This thy demaund, ï¿½ Lady, doth reuiue
He lately heard that dying Lady grone,
Had slaine Sir Mordant, and his Lady bright:
Did court the handmayd of my Lady deare,
Though she thy Lady be, approch thee neare;
And loue auowd to other Lady late,
Did dewty to their Lady, as became;
And each one sought his Lady to aggrate:
The Prince by chaunce did on a Lady light,
Loue haue I sure, (quoth she) but Lady none;
Ne to your Lady will I seruice done,
That of them cleeped was the Lady of delight.
Now were they liegemen to this Lady free,
Whom when the Lady saw so faire a wight.
The Lady did faire Britomart entreat,
Their Lady lying on the sencelesse grownd;
About their Lady first they flockt arownd,
Faire Lady she him seemd, like Lady drest,
Faire Lady she him seemd, like Lady drest,
Whose lignage from this Lady I deriue along.
Oft did he wish, that Lady faire mote bee
Serued a gentle Lady of great sway,
But Dwarfe aread, what is that Lady bright,
That Lady is (quoth he) where so she bee,
To seeke his Lady, where he mote her find;
Or riue in twaine: which when that Lady bright
And where their Lady was, arriued at the last.
Defowled, and their Lady dresse his wownd,
How him in deadly case their Lady fownd,
But loue so faire a Lady, that his life releast?
She gracious Lady, yet no paines did spare,
Ne foot could further moue: the Lady gent
That gentle Lady, whom I loue and serue,
The Witch creates a snowy Lady,
She was the Lady selfe, whom he so long had sought.
To leaue to him that Lady for excheat,
Whiles of a wanton Lady I do write,
That of his Lady they might haue the sight,
Ah fairest Lady knight, (said Paridell)
Which hath thy Lady reft, and knighthood shent,
The gentle Lady, loose at randon left,
My Lady and my loue so cruelly to pen?
My Lady and my loue is cruelly pend
For whom so faire a Lady feeles so sore a wound.
She dolefull Lady, like a dreary Spright,
And fiercely ronning to that Lady trew,
Had not the Lady, which by him stood bound,
Can wretched Lady, quit from wofull state,
Henceforth faire Lady comfort to you take,
He bound that pitteous Lady prisoner, now relest,
But she faire Lady ouercommen quight
In louely wise she gan that Lady greet,
His rouing eie did on the Lady glaunce,
And said, Sir Knight, sith ye this Lady clame,
(For so to lose a Lady, were great shame)
But if to match that Lady they had sought
Whether shall haue the Hag, or hold the Lady still.
Pursuing that faire Lady full of feare;
He held the Lady forth before him right,
And for more ioy, that captiue Lady faire
And shew'd that she had not that Lady reft,
Wherefore the Lady, which Eirena hight,
The Lady to alight did eft require,
The sight whereof the Lady sore adrad,
That he it was not, which that Lady kild,
And both the liuing Lady claime your right,
And offred streight the Lady to be slaine.
The liuing Lady, which from thee he reaued:
Him slaies, drownes Lady Munera
With noise whereof the Lady forth appeared
Least any should betray his Lady treacherously.
Till he redeemed had that Lady thrall:
Which my liege Lady seeing, thought it best,
To haue bene done against her Lady Queene,
And on his Lady, th'author of that wrong,
Vnto his scornefull Lady, that for her had sent.
There shall ye see my souerayne Lady Queene
Vnto that Lady, where he her had lore,
How that the Lady Belge now had found
Which when the Lady from the Castle saw,
Saying; Deare Lady, deedes ought not be scand
They spide a Lady left all succourlesse,
And that faire Lady, which in that vprore
As in your selfe, O soueraine Lady Queene,
Ne was there Knight, ne was there Lady found
For may no Knight nor Lady passe along
Sayd then that Squire: The Lady which doth owne
Then which a prouder Lady liueth none:
Where of the Lady selfe in sad dismay
Thereof full blyth the Lady streight became,
Therefore faire Lady lay aside this griefe,
Faire Lady let it not you seeme disgrace,
By a faire Lady, and a straunger Knight,
But that faire Lady would be cheard for nought,
But faire Priscilla (so that Lady hight)
And eke that Lady his faire louely lasse.
The fearefull Lady to her father deare,
Did yeeld; Ne lesse the Lady did aduaunce.
To solace with his Lady in delight:
And eke the Lady was full faire to see,
The faire Serena (so his Lady hight)
Who nathelesse, when he the Lady saw
Came to the place, where he his Lady found
With a faire Lady lincked by his syde,
And let thy Lady likewise doe the same.
With which rude speach his Lady much displeased,
With th'other staide his Lady vp with steddy might.
And with his Lady to the Castle rid,
And that this Lady, both whose sides are pearst
In which this Lady languisheth forlorne,
Who sitting with his Lady then at bord,
Albe his Lady, that Blandina hight,
So downe he tooke his Lady in distresse,
As euer he to Lady was affyde,
Ne euer Lady of so honest name,
The Lady, for that she was much in dred,
And eke his Lady, though she sickely were,
As such a Lady so to beate and bruse;
Yond Lady and her Squire with foule despight
See how they doe the Lady hale and draw.
Which when the Lady saw, she cryde amaine;
But tell me Lady, wherefore doe you beare
Now Lady sith your fortunes thus dispose,
Then he was tride vnto his Lady bright:
Whereas this Lady, like a sheepe astray,
The daughter of her Lady Claribell,
The same is yonder Lady, whom high God did saue.
Much was the Lady troubled at that speach,
In perfect forme, as this good Lady felt,
Or vnto louely Lady doing wrong:
That seeke a Lady,---There he suddein staid,
With which he forward lasht the laesie teme,
A laesie loord, for nothing good to donne,
Such laesinesse both lewd and poore attonce him made.
Behind her farre away a Dwarfe did lag,
When so she lagged, as she needs mote so,
After whom Lago, and Kinmarke did raine,
Them both together laid, to ioy in vaine delight.
And laid her stole aside. Her angels face
Which cunningly was without morter laid,
And goodly galleries farre ouer laid,
Home is he brought, and laid in sumptuous bed:
Nor wayld of friends, nor laid on groning beare,
Is laid away, and counterfesaunce knowne.
And euer burning wrath before him laid,
Of puissant armes, and laid in easie bed;
Which to extirpe, he laid him priuily
And double blowes about him stoutly laid,
That hath (maugre her spight) thus low me laid in dust.
And laid forth for ensample of the best:
And laid him downe vpon a grassie plaine;
Such grace now to be happy, is before thee laid.
Sir Guyon laid in swowne is by
When hauing laid his cruell bow away,
With that, rude hand vpon his shield he laid,
Whom fortune hath alreadie laid in lowest seat.
So fierce he laid about him, and dealt blowes
But laid them vp in his immortall scrine,
And oft when things were lost, or laid amis,
And laid the blame, not to his carriage,
Mainly they all attonce vpon him laid,
Whom hauing laid in comfortable couch,
Bene they all dead, and laid in dolefull herse?
There they him laid in easie couch well dight;
Then laid the noble Championesse strong hond
And laid on load with all their might and powre,
And Paridell and Druon fiercely laid
Then all that rout vppon them rudely laid,
She hewd, she foynd, she lasht, she laid on euery side.
And laid his Seneschall low on the ground,
And first laide on those Ladies thousand blames,
Laide heauy hands on him, and held so strayte,
Sad Vna downe her laies in wearie plight,
By any Ladies side for Leman to haue laine.
This Gyants sonne, that lies there on the laire
Sometime a fowle, sometime a fish in lake,
What voyce of damned Ghost from Limbo lake,
In peace may passen ouer Lethe lake,
Doest thou sit wayling by black Stygian lake,
Long fostred in the filth of Lerna lake,
In euery fountaine, and in euery lake,
Which she in Stygian lake, ay burning bright,
The Idle lake, my wandring ship I row,
That floted in the midst of that great lake:
The slouthfull waue of that great griesly lake;
That in the lake his loftie crest was steept,
Nor sea of licour cold, nor lake of mire,
Into the lake he lept, his Lord to ayd,
Late left beyond that Ydle lake, proceedes
(As wonts the Tartar by the Caspian lake,
Vntill he came vnto a standing lake;
Hedlong her selfe did cast into that lake;
Did ferry him ouer the Idle lake:
That like a little lake it seemd to bee;
During which worke the Ladie of the Lake,
Of bold Penthesilee, which made a lake
By Stygian lake I vow, whose sad annoy
From Limbo lake him late escaped sure would say.
Nigh thirtie minutes to the Southerne lake;
More loathd then Lerna, or then Stygian lake,
That at the last like to a purple lake
Witnesse the wounds, and this wyde bloudie lake,
Bred in the loathly lakes of Tartary,
And looking vp, when as his shield he lakt,
On cursed tree, of that vnspotted lam,
And by her in a line a milke white lambe she lad.
So pure and innocent, as that same lambe,
A seely Lambe farre from the flocke does take,
But trembled like a lambe, fled from the pray,
The Lyon there did with the Lambe consort,
My lambes doe euery yeare increase their score,
Vnto my Lambes, and him dislodge away;
Her other leg was lame, that she no'te walke,
And yet the one her other legge had lame,
But that lame Hag, still as abroad he strew
Thicke forest, was bescratcht, & both his feet nigh lame.
He set vpon her Palfrey tired lame,
Repentance feeble, sorrowfull, and lame:
lame.
Melting in teares, then gan she thus lament;
Heard how in vaine Fradubio did lament,
In stead of rest, she does lament, and weepe
To weet, what wight so loudly did lament.
His wandring perill closely did lament,
Then gins her grieued ghost thus to lament and mourne.
And ioyd to see her louer languish and lament.
But praying still did wake, and waking did lament.
That oft they did lament his lucklesse state,
Had with due rites and dolorous lament
That after soone I dearely did lament:
O who shall helpe me to lament, and mourne
The martiall Mayd stayd not him to lament,
Whiles all her sisters did for her lament,
And their great mother Venus did lament
But that lewd louer did the most lament
That madest many Ladies deare lament
Her selfe vppon her bed, and did lament:
Yet did she not lament with loude alew,
That for his sake Diana did lament,
What be you wofull Dame, which thus lament,
That ruth it was to see him so lament.
To see her sore lament, and bite her tender lip.
Did laugh at those that did lament and plaine:
Where day and night she nought did but lament
These eyes saw die, and dearely did lament:
But for to tell her lamentable cace,
And strow with flowres the lamentable beare:
O lamentable fall of famous towne,
And thereof made a lamentable lay,
He heard the lamentable voice of one,
He gan record the lamentable stowre,
And tell withall, the lamentable plight,
Then thus began the lamentable Dame;
Which she beheld with lamentable eye,
My life will by his death haue lamentable end.
And much lamented his calamity,
With hollow howling, and lamenting cry,
And all the way, with great lamenting paine,
As with lamenting eyes him selfe did lately vew.
Lamenting Sorrow did in darknesse lye,
Lamenting his mishap and heauy plight;
Lamenting sore his sorowfull sad tyne,
They doe thy sire, lamenting sore for thee;
Which to her selfe lamenting loudly cryde,
He spyde, lamenting her vnluckie strife,
He wept, and wayld, and false laments belyde,
With loud laments that most vnluckie stound,
And after him Sir Lamoracke of yore,
Such as a lamp, whose life does fade away:
The morow next, so soone as Phoebus Lamp
Now hath the Sunne with his lamp-burning light,
Like Phoebus lampe throughout the world doth shine,
Had spent his lampe, and brought forth dawning light,
But welcome now my light, and shining lampe of blis.
O lightsome day, the lampe of highest Ioue,
And sacred lampe in secret chamber hide,
The faithfull light of that faire lampe yblent,
The drunken lampe downe in the oyle did steepe,
Ne is that same great glorious lampe of light,
Vntill she spide the lampe of lightsome day,
And leading th'euer-burning lampe astray,
Whose goodly light then Phebus lampe doth shine more cleare?
The morrow next, before the lampe of light,
That shyning lampes in Ioues high house were light:
Those glaring lampes were set, that made a dreadfull shade.
By this th'eternall lampes, wherewith high Ioue
In stead of eyes two burning lampes she set
And heauenly lampes were halfendeale ybrent:
And both adorn'd with lampes of flaming light,
Few perling drops from her faire lampes of light;
Emongst th'eternall spheres and lamping sky,
The euer-burning lamps from thence it braught,
In her faire eyes two liuing lamps did flame,
To light their blessed lamps in Ioues eternall hous.
In whose faire eyes, like lamps of quenched fire,
That all the rest like lesser lamps did dim:
But Braggadocchio with his bloudie lance
And casting from her that enchaunted lance,
With which their liues thou lanchedst long afore,
She low let fall, that flowd from her lanck syde
And her lancke loynes vngirt, and brests vnbraste,
Lanc't through the arme, fell down with him in drerie swound.
Forwasted all their land, and them expeld:
Do backe rebut, and each to other yeeldeth land.
And fled away: for neuer in that land
And plentie, which in all the land did grow;
And quite dismembred hath: the thirstie land
My faithfull seruice, that by land and seas
Though conquered now he lie on lowly land,
A foggy mist had couered all the land;
Of doughtie knights, whom Faery land did raise,
Hath brought you hither into Faery land,
High reard their royall throne in Britane land,
That with his largenesse measured much land,
It sweepeth all the land behind him farre,
That drowned all the land, whereon he stood;
That happie land, and all with innocent blood
That all the land with stench, and heauen with horror choke.
Vere the maine shete, and beare vp with the land,
That aged Sire, the Lord of all that land,
Glad signe of victorie and peace in all their land.
To proue how many acres he did spread of land.
Vnto another loue, and to another land.
And solemne feast proclaimd throughout the land,
Where we must land some of our passengers,
Where is that happy land of Faery,
And mickle worship in his natiue land;
When with king Oberon he came to Faerie land.
The cursed land where many wend amis,
Into the land, that lay them faire before,
It was a chosen plot of fertile land,
But when as Guyon of that land had sight,
Where gladsome Guyon salied forth to land,
I labour would to guide you through all Faery land.
The land, which warlike Britons now possesse,
But farre in land a saluage nation dwelt,
Into this land by chaunce haue driuen bene,
They held this land, and with their filthinesse
This land inuaded with like violence,
Which in his land he lately did appease,
Braue moniments remaine, which yet that land enuies.
But taught the land from wearie warres to cease.
Nought else, but treason, from the first this la[n]d did foyle.
Thenceforth this land was tributarie made
Then gan the Hunnes and Picts inuade this land,
Grew great, and got large portions of land,
The royall Ofspring of his natiue land,
And fast the land behind them fled away.
That all the land they vnder them did hide;
And noblest borne of all in Britayne land;
Ne euer land beheld, ne liuing wight,
Then said the knight, Loe I the land descry,
Are not firme land, nor any certein wonne,
From the departing land it launched light,
The land, to which their course they leueled;
And the faire land it selfe did plainly show.
That with her crooked keele the land she strooke,
By sea, by land, where so they may be met,
The land to sea, and sea to maineland dry,
He wonneth in the land of Fayeree,
The powre of forrein Paynims, which inuade thy land.
And high accompt throughout all Elfin land,
So safetie found at sea, which she found not at land.
Thence backe returning to the former land,
The land for sea, at randon there to raunge:
Least worse on sea then vs on land befell.
To fetch from sea, that ye at land lost late;
Confounds both land & seas, and skyes doth ouercast.
Toward the land; two riuers bound the rest.
On foot, vpon the face of liuing land?
Vnto her rest in Plutoes griesly land,
For either they were left vppon the land,
For whylome they haue conquerd sea and land,
But that he was full light and nimble on the land.
Tydings of all, which there had hapned on the land.
And eke of Lordship, with both land and fee:
Of all her land and lordship during life:
Which afterward both sea and land possest:
Yet quaile in conquest of that land of gold.
Next these the plenteous Ouse came far from land,
And Twede the limit betwixt Logris land
Whose fruitfull seede farre passeth those in land,
But from the water to the land betooke his flight.
Aboue the brincke, to tread vpon the land,
Encroch vppon the land there vnder thee;
And by him brought againe to Faerie land;
The most part of my land hath washt away,
And though my land he first did winne away,
Full true it is, what so about our land
Your brothers land the which the sea hath layd
So Amidas, the land was yours first hight,
Had long beheld, her selfe vppon the land
Vnto the land of Amazons, as she was bent.
That like a stone it fell vpon the land,
With which high God had blest her happie land,
And witnesse forth aright in forrain land,
Farre thence from forrein land, where they did dwell,
Her land, and slaine her children ruefully alas.
Which brought that land to his subiection,
From that sad land, where he his syre did quell,
Within the land, where dwelt that Ladie sad,
They came vnto a Citie farre vp land,
So long had done, and from her natiue land
And euer ere he saw the stroke to land,
And all the people both of towne and land,
Which them forbad to land, and footing did forstall.
But nathemore would they from land refraine,
That they lay scattred ouer all the land,
Tho as he backe returned from that land,
In this delightfull land of Faery,
Nor land nor fee, for hyre of his good deede,
Into some forrein land, where as no need
Into the land of Faerie, where no wight
Into this land, where I haue wond thus long,
Of all this land, late conquer'd by his sword
So is my Lord now seiz'd of all the land,
And all this land with endlesse losse to ouerflow.
